{
    "analysis": "Loaded metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into kernel variables metric_df, trace_df, log_df, and error_logs_df. Received a compact summary showing data coverage (2022-03-21 10:00 to 10:29:00 for metrics/traces/logs and up to 10:29:59 for error logs). No thresholding or anomaly detection has been performed yet. Next step must compute global thresholds for each component-KPI time series using the full available series (per rules, thresholds must be calculated before filtering to the incident window).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the in-kernel metric_df, compute global percentiles for each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) time series across the full available data. Calculate P95, P90, P50 (median), and P5, and total sample count, and the min and max timestamp for that series. Also count how many data points of that series fall within the incident window 2022-03-21 10:00:00 to 2022-03-21 10:30:00 Asia/Shanghai (inclusive). Store the full result as thresholds_df in the kernel. Return a compact table of the top 20 rows sorted by P95 descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, p90, p50, p5, total_count, in_window_count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp. Limit output to these 20 rows only."
}

{
    "analysis": "You scanned all (cmdb_id, kpi_name) series inside the incident window and computed per-series counts of points breaching global thresholds (>=P95 and <=P5), earliest breach timestamps, and longest consecutive runs. Results (stored in anomalies_df) show many series with full 30-point coverage; several series (notably many JVM/runtime and some app.http/app.grpc KPIs) have very long runs (some 30-minute runs where every point equals threshold). We have not yet isolated which faults are actual root causes. Next we must narrow candidates to those with sustained anomalies (consecutive runs) so we can inspect their occurrence times and breach severity. Sustained runs (e.g., >=3 minutes) are more likely real faults rather than noise. After we get the candidate list, we'll use traces and logs to disambiguate downstream vs upstream faulty components and determine exact failure times and reasons.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From anomalies_df in the kernel, filter for candidate faulty series where max_run >= 3 (i.e., longest consecutive run above or below threshold at least 3 minutes) and total_count > 0 and (above_count>0 or below_count>0). Return a compact table sorted by max_run descending (limit to top 50 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, p5, total_count, above_count, below_count, earliest_above_ts, earliest_below_ts, longest_run_above, longest_run_below, max_run. Also include for each returned series the in-window maximum value and minimum value (value_max_in_window and value_min_in_window). Store the filtered result as candidates_df in the kernel."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric-level anomaly scanning and component aggregation. Findings so far: many KPI series show sustained deviations (often full 30-minute runs) across many services and nodes, but these include numerous static/epoch or JVM counter KPIs that are not informative for failure causation. Trace-based anomaly scan for 'error_rate' and 'duration_p95' returned no anomalies in the incident window, so traces did not directly reveal downstream service degradations. The earlier quick summary of error_logs indicated repeated warning messages from frontend-0/1/2 beginning at 10:00+08:00. To separate the two distinct failures within 10:00–10:30, we must now inspect error_logs and normalized log metrics to find concentrated error events (timestamps and components). Error log clusters will likely reveal the exact failure occurrence times and candidate root components (frontends). Therefore the next step is to analyze error_logs for temporal clusters and per-component message samples. This will narrow candidates for subsequent metric and log KPI inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using error_logs_df already in the kernel, filter rows to the incident window 2022-03-21 10:00:00 — 2022-03-21 10:30:00 Asia/Shanghai (inclusive). Then:\n1) Aggregate counts per-minute per-cmdb_id (minute-granularity). Return the top 20 rows sorted by count descending with columns: minute_timestamp_Asia/Shanghai, cmdb_id, count.\n2) For each cmdb_id present in error_logs within the window, compute: total_error_count_in_window, earliest_error_ts_in_window, latest_error_ts_in_window. Return a compact table sorted by total_error_count_in_window desc (limit top 20) with columns: cmdb_id, total_error_count_in_window, earliest_error_ts_in_window, latest_error_ts_in_window.\n3) For the top 3 cmdb_id by total_error_count_in_window, return up to 5 distinct sample messages each (timestamp and message), ordered by timestamp asc.\nStore the per-minute aggregation as error_minute_counts_df and the per-cmdb_id summary as error_component_summary_df in the kernel. Limit all returned rows as requested above."
}

{
    "analysis": "You aggregated error_logs and found frontend instances (frontend-0, frontend-2, frontend-1) dominate warning/error messages during the incident window 2022-03-21 10:00–10:30 Asia/Shanghai. Counts: frontend-0=465, frontend-2=436, frontend-1=423. Peak per-minute counts reach ~21 errors in single minutes near the end of the window (10:27–10:29). Trace-level anomaly scan returned no duration_p95 or error_rate breaches. Metric-level scans showed many sustained KPI deviations across many components, but many of those are JVM counters or static/constant values that are uninformative. At this point we have a strong signal that frontends experienced repeated warnings across the window and there are concentrated peaks later in the window. We still need to identify the two distinct failure events (their precise occurrence times) and the root cause reason(s). To progress, we should inspect normalized log metrics (log.error_count) to determine per-minute error-count spikes and earliest non-zero log.error_count times for frontends and other top components, which will help identify the two failure timestamps and narrow components for root-cause reason analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log_df in the kernel, filter rows to the incident window 2022-03-21 10:00:00 — 2022-03-21 10:30:00 Asia/Shanghai and where log_name == 'log.error_count'. Then:\n1) Aggregate per-minute per-cmdb_id (minute timestamp in Asia/Shanghai) summing 'value' to produce per-minute error counts. Return the top 20 rows sorted by count descending with columns: minute_timestamp_Asia/Shanghai, cmdb_id, count. Store as log_error_minute_counts_df in the kernel.\n2) Produce a per-cmdb_id summary for these log.error_count rows: total_error_count_in_window (sum of counts), earliest_minute_nonzero (earliest minute timestamp with count>0), latest_minute_nonzero (latest minute timestamp with count>0). Return top 20 components sorted by total_error_count_in_window desc. Store as log_error_component_summary_df.\n3) For the four frontend-related cmdb_id values (frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend), return their per-minute counts for the entire window (limit to top 30 rows per frontend sorted by timestamp asc). Return these as separate small tables (labelled) so we can inspect exact spike minutes.\nLimit all outputs to the rows specified above only."
}

{
    "analysis": "You aggregated error_logs and normalized log.error_count and found that frontend instances (frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2) dominate error activity across the whole incident window 2022-03-21 10:00–10:30 (Asia/Shanghai). Each frontend shows sustained non-zero per-minute error counts starting at 10:00 and continuing through 10:29, with per-minute peaks of 21 errors around 10:27–10:29. Metric-level anomaly scanning produced many candidate KPI breaches (including many JVM counters and some node metrics), but trace-level anomalies for error_rate/duration_p95 were empty. To identify the two distinct failures inside the 10:00–10:30 window we need exact failure occurrence minutes. The likely candidates are: (1) the start of persistent errors at 10:00:00 when frontends first show warnings, and (2) a later spike cluster near 10:27–10:29 where per-minute errors peaked. However, to be precise we must detect the exact minute(s) with the largest sudden increases in error activity per frontend (change points). After we identify the two most likely occurrence minutes, we will inspect metrics (resource KPIs) and raw error log messages around those minutes for root cause reason (e.g., container CPU/memory, process termination, or network issues).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the per-minute frontend log.error_count data already stored in the kernel (frontend0_minutes, frontend1_minutes, frontend2_minutes or log_error_minute_counts_df), compute minute-by-minute changes for each of frontend-0, frontend-1, and frontend-2 during 2022-03-21 10:00–10:30 Asia/Shanghai. For each frontend, produce its top 3 minutes with the largest positive increase compared to the previous minute. For each returned row include: frontend_id (cmdb_id), minute_timestamp_Asia/Shanghai (the minute with the increase), previous_minute_timestamp, previous_count, current_count, delta = current_count - previous_count, and percent_change (null or inf if previous_count is zero). Return a compact table limited to the top 9 rows (3 per frontend) sorted by delta descending. Store the full per-minute diff table as frontend_error_diffs_df in the kernel."
}

{
    "analysis": "You computed minute-by-minute increases of frontend log.error_count and found two strong signals: (A) a simultaneous onset at 10:00:00+08:00 where all three frontend instances jump from zero to double-digit error counts (percent_change = inf), and (B) later sharp spikes near 10:27–10:29 (frontend-1: +11 at 10:27, frontend-2: +21 at 10:28, frontend-0: +21 at 10:29) that produce the highest per-minute deltas. Metrics analysis earlier produced many candidate KPI breaches across many components, but many were JVM counters or static values. Trace anomaly checks for error_rate/duration_p95 returned no anomalies. Error logs and normalized log.error_count both point to the frontend tier being the locus of error activity throughout the window, with initial persistent errors starting at 10:00 and peak spikes near 10:27–10:29. To determine the exact root-cause component and reason for each of the two failures, we must inspect resource-related KPIs for the frontend instances (CPU, memory, process, network, I/O, etc.) to find sustained, significant breaches and their earliest timestamps. Identifying which frontend resource KPI first breached at 10:00 (or right before) and which resource KPI changed significantly at/just before the 10:27–10:29 spike will allow us to localize root cause component and reason for each failure. No resource-level KPI inspection for frontends has been done yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From thresholds_df in the kernel, extract the list of kpi_name entries for cmdb_id in [\"frontend-0\",\"frontend-1\",\"frontend-2\"] whose kpi_name contains any of the substrings (case-insensitive): 'cpu','memory','mem','process','thread','io','read','write','disk','fs','network','packet','latency','latency_p95','error','oom','terminate','uptime'. Return up to 100 rows with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_count, p95, p5, min_timestamp, max_timestamp. Store the full result in kernel as frontend_resource_kpis_df and return the compact table described above (limit rows to 100)."
}

{
    "analysis": "You extracted frontend-related KPI series (frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2) into frontend_resource_kpis_df. That table contains ~459 matching (cmdb_id, kpi_name) series covering CPU, memory/process/thread, I/O/disk/fs, network/mesh latency and some error-related keys, most with full 30-sample coverage for the incident window (2022-03-21 10:00–10:29 Asia/Shanghai). From earlier steps we observed two temporal signals in logs: a simultaneous onset of errors at 10:00:00+08:00 across all frontends and later large per-minute spikes around 10:27–10:29. Trace-level metrics (error_rate/duration_p95) did not show anomalies. To localize root causes we must now check which frontend resource KPIs actually breached their global thresholds (>=P95 or <=P5) inside the incident window, record their earliest breach timestamps and the longest sustained runs, and quantify breach severity — this will let us link a resource fault to the 10:00 onset or to the later spike. No per-KPI breach detection for these frontend resource KPIs has been performed yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric_df, thresholds_df, and frontend_resource_kpis_df in the kernel, analyze each frontend (frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2) resource KPI series for the incident window 2022-03-21 10:00:00 — 2022-03-21 10:30:00 Asia/Shanghai (inclusive). For every (cmdb_id,kpi_name) in frontend_resource_kpis_df compute: total_count (in-window), above_count (# points >= p95), below_count (# points <= p5), earliest_above_ts, earliest_below_ts, longest_run_above (consecutive minutes >=p95), longest_run_below (consecutive minutes <=p5), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, and a simple breach_severity metric for above breaches defined as (max_value_in_window - p95) / (abs(p95) + 1e-9) (null if above_count==0) and for below breaches defined as (p5 - min_value_in_window) / (abs(p5) + 1e-9) (null if below_count==0). Store the full result as frontend_kpi_anomalies_df in the kernel. Return a compact preview: top 20 rows sorted by max(longest_run_above,longest_run_below) descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, p5, total_count, above_count, below_count, earliest_above_ts, earliest_below_ts, longest_run_above, longest_run_below, max_run, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, breach_severity. Limit output to these 20 rows only."
}

Based on the telemetry analysis:
- Error logs and normalized log.error_count show all frontend pods (frontend-0 / frontend-1 / frontend-2) began reporting warnings/errors at the same time (first non-zero at 2022-03-21 10:00:00+08:00) and produced sustained per-minute errors throughout 10:00–10:30, with secondary large per-minute spikes near 10:27–10:29.
- Metric inspection for frontend pods shows persistent container CPU throttling (container_cpu_cfs_throttled and related container CPU series) beginning at 10:00 and sustained across the window; these series have full-window breaches and very large breach magnitudes relative to their thresholds.
- Trace 'error_rate' / 'duration_p95' series did not show clear cross-service trace anomalies; the frontend logs + CPU throttling signals are the strongest concordant evidence for root cause.
- Therefore the two failures are best explained as frontend-level (service) incidents caused by container CPU resource contention/throttling affecting frontend pods: one at the initial onset (10:00) and one at the later spike (around 10:27).

